\begin_layout Standard
A growing literature documents that wage returns to experience have changed
 for U.S.
 workers over the post-war period.
 An early literature showed that cross-sectional wage profiles became steeper
 over time (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

 for the period 1963-1987).
 A more recent literature has focused on longitudinal wage growth as a given
 cohort accumulates experience.
 Notably, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kambourov2005accounting"

\end_inset

 document a flattening of experience profiles over the birth cohorts 1950-1970,
 while 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kongRaviExplaining"

\end_inset

 document a similar flattening for the cohorts born between 1915 and 1955.
 Additional evidence suggests that the changes in returns to experience
 differ across school groups.
 Notably, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CardLemieux2001"

\end_inset

 show that the cross-sectional college wage premium evolves differently
 for young and old workers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These findings have spawned a literature that seeks to explain time-varying
 returns to experience.
 There are two main themes in this literature:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\emph on
price
\emph default
 of experience has changed over time.
 According to this view, old and young workers supply different labor inputs.
 As their relative supplies change over time, so do their relative prices
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KatzMurphy1992,CardLemieux2001,jeong2015price"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\emph on
quantity
\emph default
 of experience has changed over time.
 According to this view, the rate at which cohorts accumulate human capital
 varies over time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guvenen2010nber,kongRaviExplaining"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this paper is to offer an alternative explanation.
 The idea is that longitudinal changes in returns to experience reflect
 time-varying wage growth as cohorts age.
 Cross-sectional changes in returns to experience reflect time-varying cohort
 qualities.
 According to this view, neither the price nor the quantity of experience
 accumulated by a cohort change over time.
\end_layout

