\begin_layout Standard
The paper's objective is to show that a simple model accounts well for the
 changes in age-wage profiles observed in CPS data.
 The model should be parsimonious to avoid 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overfitting.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 It should contain 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 ingredients that have been found useful in previous research.
 These considerations motivate the choice of the main model elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A nested CES aggregate production function with constant skill-biased technical
 change.
 This is a minor extension of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

, who consider only two school classes (college, no college).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Cohort qualities 
\begin_inset Formula $\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}$
\end_inset

 that are a function of the cohort's average years of schooling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Time invariant age-efficiency profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Aggregate production function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Output is produced from human capital augmented labor according to the nested
 CES aggregator
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\aggrOutput_{\pYear}=\neutralProd_{\pYear}\left[G_{\pYear}^{\cesRho_{CG}}+(\skillWeight_{CG,\pYear}\lSupply_{CG,\pYear})^{\cesRho_{CG}}\right]^{1/\cesRho_{CG}}\label{eq:AggrProdFct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G_{\tau}=\left[\sum_{s=HSD}^{CD}(\skillWeight_{s,\pYear}\lSupply_{s,\pYear})^{\rho_{HS}}\right]^{1/\rho_{HS}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is a CES aggregator for unskilled labor (with less than a college degree)
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lSupply$
\end_inset

 denotes labor input in efficiency units.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\cesRho_{HS}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cesRho_{CG}$
\end_inset

 govern the elasticities of substitution of the labor inputs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\neutralProd_{\pYear}$
\end_inset

 is an exogenous neutral productivity sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

, relative skill weights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\skillWeight_{s,\pYear}/\skillWeight_{HSG,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to grow at constant rates (constant skill-biased technical
 change): 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\skillWeight_{\sIndex,\pYear}-\ln\skillWeight_{HSG,\pYear}=\muIntercept_{\sIndex}+\grRate\left(\skillWeight_{\sIndex}\right)\left(\pYear-\wageYearOne\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In each year, the skill weights are normalized to sum to 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only departure from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

 is that I consider four school groups instead of two.
 Treating college graduates as separate from college dropouts allows the
 model to capture the large rise in the college wage premium since the 1980s
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

 and more recently 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "AutorKK2008"

\end_inset

).
 Throughout, I define the college premium as the gap in log median wages
 between college graduates and high school graduates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Labor inputs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Labor inputs in efficiency units are given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lSupply_{s,\pYear}=\sum_{\age=\ageWorkStart_{s}}^{\lifeSpan}\aggrHours_{\age,\sIndex,\pYear}h_{\age,s}\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}\label{eq:LaborMarket}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here, it is assumed that persons in school group 
\begin_inset Formula $\sIndex$
\end_inset

 work from age 
\begin_inset Formula $\ageWorkStart_{\sIndex}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lifeSpan$
\end_inset

.
 Hours worked 
\begin_inset Formula $\aggrHours_{\age,\sIndex,\pYear}$
\end_inset

 and age efficiency profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

 are taken as exogenous.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LaborMarket"

\end_inset

 defines 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cohort quality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as the intercept of the cohort's age-efficiency profile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Wages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unobserved skill prices equal marginal products: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sPrice_{\sIndex,\pYear}=\frac{\partial\aggrOutput_{\sIndex,\pYear}}{\partial\lSupply_{\sIndex,\pYear}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Observed wages equal skill prices times labor efficiency:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\wage_{\age,\sIndex,\pYear}=\sPrice_{\sIndex,\pYear}h_{\age,\sIndex}\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}\label{eq:Wage}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Cohort quality:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, I assume that cohort quality is a quadratic function of
 average years of schooling: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear} & =\cqBeta_{\sIndex,1}\cohSchool_{\bYear}+\cqBeta_{\sIndex,2}\cohSchool_{\bYear}^{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This captures the idea that expanding schooling is associated with declining
 average abilities of workers in all school groups (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "LHAbil"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding a linear time trend to cohort qualities would not change any of the
 paper's implications.
 Adjusting the experience-efficiency profiles and the time paths of skill
 prices using appropriate linear trends would generate the same cohort wage
 profiles as reported here.
 This is the flip side of the well-known problem of identifying cohort,
 time, and age effects 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schulhofer2011"

\end_inset

.
 However, the assumption of no trend in cohort qualities is important for
 decomposing observed growth in wages into the contributions of skill price
 growth and human capital growth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Calibration"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following parameters are estimated jointly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Neutral productivities 
\begin_inset Formula $\neutralProd_{\pYear}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative skill weights and their growth rates: 
\begin_inset Formula $\muIntercept_{\sIndex}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\grRate\left(\skillWeight_{\sIndex}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Age-efficiency profiles: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

.
 For the sake of parsimony, 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

 is modeled as a quartic polynomial in experience 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\age-\ageWorkStart_{\sIndex}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Using age dummies instead makes essentially no difference.
 A quartic polynomial approximates the estimated age-efficiency profiles
 very well.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cohort qualities: 
\begin_inset Formula $\cqBeta_{\sIndex,j}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The estimation approach is weighted least squares.
 The objective to be minimized is the weighted sum of squared deviations
 between log model wages (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Wage"

\end_inset

) and log median data wages:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\sum_{s=1}^{S}\sum_{\age=\age_{s}}^{\qAgeMax}\sum_{\bYear=\bYearFirst}^{\bYearLast}\pWeight_{\age,s,\bYear}\left[\ln\wage_{\age,s,\bYear}-\ln\hat{\wage}_{\age,s,\bYear}\right]^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Observations for which data do not exist (
\begin_inset Formula $\pYear=\bYear+\age-1<\wageYearOne$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $>\wageYearLast$
\end_inset

) are, of course, dropped.
 The weight of each cell 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\pWeight\right)$
\end_inset

 is the square root of the number of observations.
 The estimation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{\sIndex=1}^{\sMax}\left(\lifeSpan-\ageWorkStart_{\sIndex}\right)\times\left(\wageYearLast-\wageYearOne+1\right)\approx4\times35\times46=6,440$
\end_inset

 data moments to estimate 80 parameters.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For each school group, we have: 1 intercept, 4 experience quartic parameters,
 2 cohort quality parameters, 2 skill weight parameters (except for HSG).
 Total number of parameters is therefore 34 plus 46 for the neutral productiviti
es 
\begin_inset Formula $\neutralProd_{\pYear}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, the model does not trivially fit the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimating the model would be slightly complicated due to the fact that
 skill prices are not observable.
 Fortunately, it turns out that a simpler approach is available.
 This involves the following steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Regress log median wages in each (age, school, year) cell on an intercept,
 a quartic in experience (that estimates 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

), time dummies 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ln\sPrice_{\sIndex,\pYear}\right)$
\end_inset

, and a quadratic in cohort schooling 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ln\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is done separately for each school group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Construct aggregate labor supplies from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LaborMarket"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recover the skill weights from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Wage"

\end_inset

 and verify that they are consistent with constant skill-biased technical
 change.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively, the reason why this approach 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

works
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is that time variation in relative labor supplies is dominated by variation
 in hours worked in each (age, school) group.
 Variation in labor efficiency per hour worked is relatively small.
 Thus, the model yields skill prices that are similar to what would be obtained
 from the procedure proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KatzMurphy1992"

\end_inset

, except that four school groups are used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only the last step (recovering the skill weights) depends on substitution
 elasticities of labor inputs.
 Since the results of interest do not depend on their values, I simply fix
 the substitution elasticities at 
\begin_inset Formula $\substElastInner$
\end_inset

 for the inner aggregator 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and at 
\begin_inset Formula $\substElastOuter$
\end_inset

 for the outer aggregator of the aggregate production function 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AggrProdFct"

\end_inset

.
 Changing these values would alter the recovered skill weights, but not
 the estimated values of 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\sPrice_{\sIndex,\pYear}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

