reference "sec:Estimation-Results"

\end_inset

), the model replicates the key feature observed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:WageGrowthExperAggr"

\end_inset

: returns to experience closely track log median wage growth over a cohort's
 life-cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implication is fundamental: 
\emph on
changes in skill price growth rates over time are sufficient to account
 for time-varying returns to experience
\emph default
.
 Viewed from this perspective, time varying longitudinal returns to experience
 are not a puzzle.
 In particular, accounting for them does not require time-varying age-efficiency
 profiles or time-varying relative prices of experience, which is what the
 literature has emphasized (see the references cited in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:Introduction"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be clear: The evidence presented here does not in any way demonstrate
 that the models proposed in the literature are invalid or flawed.
 It does, however, offer an alternative and simpler explanation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cross-sectional Returns to Experience
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:CsReturnExper"

\end_inset

 shows cross-sectional returns to experience, defined as the difference
 in log median wages between workers aged 
\begin_inset Formula $\experAgeLast$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\experAgeOne$
\end_inset

.
 Broadly speaking, for workers without a college degree, returns to experience
 increase until the mid 1980s and then flatten out.
 For college graduates, the pattern is very different (rising until around
 1975; falling until 1985; then rising until the end of the sample period).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model's ability to replicate the observed time variation in returns
 is mixed.
 For high school dropouts, the model is essentially unsuccessful.
 This reflects the observation, made earlier, that the model does not fit
 the observed age wage profiles for this group particularly well (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Model-Fit"

\end_inset

).
 For the other groups, the model replicates the observed low-frequency changes
 in returns, but the amplitudes are somewhat smaller than in the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With constant age-efficiency profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\age,\sIndex}$
\end_inset

, the model implies that changes in cross-sectional return to experience
 are entirely due to cohort qualities.
 Specifically, the cross-sectional return in the model is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\ln h_{\experAgeLast,\sIndex}-\ln h_{\experAgeOne,\sIndex}\right)+\mbox{\Delta}_{\bYear}\ln\cohortQuality_{\sIndex,\bYear}$
\end_inset

.
 The first term is time invariant.
 The second term is the difference in the qualities of the cohorts aged
 
\begin_inset Formula $\experAgeLast$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\experAgeOne$
\end_inset

 in a given year.
 Given the simple specification of cohort effects, the mixed model fit is
 perhaps to be expected.
\end_layout

